When I visited Vietnam in 1993,  I learned that in Vietnam, the war was over. The Vietnamese I spoke with and met on the streets of HaNoi, Vinh, Hue, DaNang, Nha Trang, SaiGon, Can Tho all welcomed me as an American.  I was caught off-balance: how could a grandmother who lost her sons and daughters to American ammunition greet me so warmly?  How could a son, whose father was killed by a bombing raid in the Iron Triangle area of South Vietnam show me such kindness? Though the war was over, the displays of kindness and affection that I experienced moved me deeply.
<p>
In the United States, however, the war is still being fought.   The war continues to haunt veterans and civilians alike, the war continues to divide families, the war remains an undercurrent within American culture and society today.
<p>
L. Grivetti<br>
