Earl Martin here again:
<p>
I'm losing track -- still a novice at this email stuff -- but someone said they'd like to hear more  from those of us who were in Vietnam about what Vietnamese felt.
<p>
Of course, none of us is qualified to summarize that.  Even in our case when we spoke Vietnamese fluently and had many close Vietnamese friends:
<p>
  1) we learned there was a broad diversity of opinions about the war and
American involvement, and<br>
  2) they tended to tell us what they thought we wanted to hear.
<p>
An example of the latter: I lived about seven kilometers from My Lai at the time of the massacre there.  (In fact I was married in that town of Quang Ngai on March 15, 1968, one day before the massacre.)  Though we heard some indirect references from a few children about atrocities, we never really heard the story of My Lai until it broke back in the States.
<p>
By the way, I was present at My Lai on March 16, 1993, on the 25th anniversary of the massacre.  I talked with many farmers, including one woman whose parents and three sisters had been killed on that fateful day.  This Mrs. Nhung herself had been in that tragic irrigation ditch that became the village's mass grave, but as a 13-year-old girl at the time, she survived because she lay under the bodies of the others who had fallen.
<p>
The amazing thing to me was that as I talked with Mrs. Nhung under the coconut tree there near the My Lai memorial, I sensed no bitterness from her at all toward any Americans.  Indeed, she expressed deep sadness at the loss of her parents, but I found no bitterness.  It's as though she accepted the loss and believed there was no point to a bitterness which would further consume her spirit.
<p>
In fact, from all the people I talked with in My Lai, including farmers, students, or officials, I truly felt that Lt. William Calley, who led the massacre, or his superior, Captain Ernest Medina, would be shown dignity and politeness if they were to visit My Lai today.
<p>
On that 25th anniversary gathering with about 1,000 folks, I pulled aside and knelt by the irrigation ditch, planted some incense that I had been given, and observed a moment of prayerful silence.  I felt a hand on my arm.  Then another on my back.  I opened my moist eyes to look into the eyes of young children, intrigued by this American who had been in their gathering.  In those eyes I saw hope.  
<p>
My very strong impression is that, for the Vietnamese, the war truly is over.
<p>
In peace, <br>
