Earl has stated his belief that, "for the Vietnamese, the war is truly over."
<p>
I have often felt that the "life view" of many Asian philosophies encourages such healing. For many, this life is but a way station on a greater cosmic path. Their cultural attachment to ancestors brings the course of life's adversity into a manageable perspective. Their ancestors are always "there" for them.
<p>
I have heard accounts that many Vietnam veterans who have visited Vietnam experienced the same feelings that the wounds of war are rapidly healing for the Vietnamese people. In a conversation with a Vietnamese American who is constantly traveling to Vietnam, he informed me that there are Vietnam veterans who are actually retiring at Vung Tau. 
<p>
The observations I've heard that strike me most come from those who contend that Vietnam veterans are viewed as honorable warriors by the Vietnamese people, and are respected as such. There seems to be some truth in this. 
<p>
I ask myself would I feel better about myself and the war if I returned to Vietnam?
<p>
Beyond the emotional pain of such an adventure, if what I am being told now is true, the answer is .....yes.
<p>
This is such a sad commentary on things, isn't it?
<p>
Thank you, Earl.
<p>
