About five years ago I saw an art exhibit about the war.  What was most striking to me was this:
<p>
The American artworks tended to be extremely expressionistic, fragmented and chaotic.  Their content totally overwhelmed and obliterated any possible context.
<p>
The Vietnamese artworks tended to be very intense, but constrained within conventional frameworks.  Unlike the American works, they were almost all framed.  And they were almost all, in one way or another, contained within landscapes.  
<p>
It seemed to me tht this said everything about the difference between us with respect to the war. 
<p>
For the Vietnamese it was a terrible experience, but one that existed within the framework of their history, their culture, their homeland.
<p>
For the Americans it was a terrible experience for which there WAS no frame of reference and, because of this, no possibility of containing and understanding the the suffering involved, no hope of learning lessons.  There was simply the experience of being overwhelmed.  It did not happen in our homeland and, in a way, it did not happen in our history--it did not fit into the myth that of history, the very myth which lead us there.  
<p>
Of course, these were overall impressions.  There were exceptions. There were some very powerful American works which did use traditional devices for providing context, though as I recall that most of these were modernist kinds of devices, such as assemblages.  These were all, if seemed to me, like personal or family memorials, rather than the kinds of culturally-shared works of the Vietnamese. 
<p>
If you recall, when the Vietnam War Memorial was first proposed, there was a terrible attack on it from conservative quarters.  It was not a proper monument to strife, triumph and glory.  But seeing this exhibit of art works, it was obvious to me why they were so wrong and why the Vietnam War Memorial is so right, so powerful.  It is like those personal family memorials--the few that managed to provide some contexts -- but unlike them it really is a culturally-shared work, something extremely difficult for Americans to produce, but something that is extremely necessary for us.
<p>
We are trying, always, to make things perfect and whole, to recover, so that there is an end to suffering.  But this is delusion and can only cause untold uneccessary suffering.  We must not forget or deny suffering, any more than we should strive to hold onto it.  We must remain aware of it, allow ourselves, over time, to learn from it.  Never forget it, or, as Santayan warned, we are doomed to repeat it.
<p>
