It's Hoaithi (y.t.) here and I will attempt to be brief. (They don't teach that in law school, so I ask for your forebearance.)
<p>
I feel a certain responsibility to comment on the question of what the Vietnamese feel because I think that I am the only Vietnamese-American in the group, and also the youngest member.  But first a disclaimer.
<p>
As I shared in my introduction, I have done no extensive research on this topic. What I am sharing with you all is distilled from personal experience and that of my family and friends. I also had the privilege of working within the Vietnamese community in Orange County, California, for a number of years so I will venture to share some of the popular--or not so popular opinions--held by many vocal members of the community. I am NOT speaking for the community but will probably be chastised for this by the community elders, one way or another. Here goes my (already doomed) political career!
<p>
I was surprised by Lou's stats of how many Vietnamese-Americans would chose to go back and would fight the communists again. I am not challenging his sources or the methods by which these figures were arrived at, though they remain unclear. They just do not ring true, given my reality. 
<p>
I would think the numbers for both questions would be higher than that. Or could it be that I am privvy to an extended group that was--and is--militantly opposed to the Vietnamese Communist government?  It's possible, since the Vietnamese-Americans in Little Saigon tend to be a lot more conservative and militant in their views regarding the current Vietnamese regime. 
<p>
With that as background, I would like to point out a couple of considerations that may possibly inform your thoughts on whether or not the war is over from a Vietnamese perspective.
<p>
First of all, there is NO one single Vietnamese perspective. That statement seems so basic, yet in our effort and great hope to make sense of things and try to come to some understanding, we tend to forget that. Vietnamese opinion regarding the war, whether or not it's over, and the aftermath is as diverse as the American perspective. You all are so fortunate that you have been discussing the issues and are trying to come to some resolution. I don't think the Vietnamese community has come that far. There is a lot more dissention, name-calling, and labelling than there are discussions. This is another generalization--like those I  warned us against earlier--but different views vary by generation, class and levels of American acculturation.
<p>
My friends and I often wonder why the militance against the current Vietnamese regime is necessary. We, too, like to say that the war is over. The idea of supporting an insurgency movement in Vietnam is not appealing to us, to say the least. We would rather concentrate our efforts and talents on seeing what else we can do to assist those at home in overcoming their impoverished reality.  
<p>
But that view is not popular among our parents. I think somebody asked that when the US normalized relations with Vietnam, did we feel betrayed? Again, I can't speak for everyone, but I know plenty of people who would answer in the affirmative--in numbers greater than those who support the policy. 
<p>
My own parents were vehemently opposed to my returning to Vietnam for the first time in 1991. My reason for returning was personal. I had not seen my grandparents and members
of my extended family for ten years. I also needed to heal some wounds of my own.  But theirs my parents' objection was political.  They would not support the Vietnamese communists with their hard-earned dollars.  They also felt that those who went to Vietnam were ready to forgive the communists of all the atrocities and lies they perpetrated on the people. They were not ready to send the same message.  Hatreds run deep and grudges are held dear, so I don't know if they ever will ever say that the war is over. It's the same with my father's air force buddies, whom I call uncles. 
<p>
As their children, people of my generation are fortunate enough to have SOME detachment; we don't share the same view, but we understand it.  They endured so much loss and suffered too much humiliation.  I look at my father with his broken spirit and the physical ailments that plague him as the result of his days in labor camps, and I understand.  So, I leave the subject alone.
<p>
At some point, though, I think in my effort to be respectful of my father and the community's elders, I and many of my friends who are deemed to be the next generation of community leaders let them get away from working through the issues with us. We don't have a tradition of free and open discussion in our culture. "Respect your elders" is the moral imperative. As the result, I think we inherited a lot of their bitterness unwillingly but unconsciously. We realize that there were a lot of problems with the South Vietnamese government during the war and how that contributed to why we no longer have a homeland, but we are not able to discuss that openly with our elders. We tell ourselves that it's still too soon to pick at the scabs.  So, we attempt to piece together what we can for ourselves.
<p>
With regard to your experience of finding reconcilation and closure in the Vietnamese people when you visit Vietnam, I wonder on what evidence did you base that observation?  If it's because the people were more than ready and willing to befriend you, I don't think that's much of an indication.  ( I don't mean any disrespect, of course.) It may be tied to our colonial history and mentality, but the fact is we are fascinated by foreigners. We worship Americans.  Always have. Even more so now that the communist propaganda has backfired and failed to deliver prosperity with peace. Capitalism is rampant in Saigon, and I wonder if the hospitality you experienced was not the result of a trend to court foreign investments.
<p>
Maybe we needed to define what we mean when we say that the war is over. Yes, literally, it is over. But I don't see the wounds healing as rapidly as someone suggested.  Why do you say the wounds have healed?  Because we can go on and rebuild the country?  Even manage to experiment with capitalism?  Of course we can. We've had to. The Vietnamese are an extremely resilient people. We have a long history of recovering from foreign invasions and colonialism. But in people's homes, pictures of loved ones who died in the war or lost their lives at sea as they attempted to flee the country are remembered on the family's altar. 
<p>
What struck me on my trip back is how, in every single home that I was in, I saw the same altar arrangement. I made a point to ask who they'd lost and how, when I could. Invariably, tears welled up. Is it not possible that the Vietnamese continue to mourn their losses, but lack the words to articulate their resentment of the injustice of it all? 
<p>
One last point (I promise)--I think it's also an important factor that the Vietnamese in Vietnam have been living under the communist regime. While we are able to learn and discuss, somewhat openly, the impact of the war and the betrayal we felt by virtue of our government's policy, the Vietnamese do not have the same opportunity. For the majority of the people, what they know of the war is through personal experience and communist propaganda.  I don't think they've had an opportunity to learn and process all of the political and morally objectionable decisions that were made regarding the war. 
<p>
Until then, aloha.<br>
