Tra Binh was a pacification village in Quang Ngai Province that my unit helped establish. Actually we built the fortifications - barbed wire, bunkers, etc.
<p>
A small girl of six or seven years befriended me. There were always little kids anywhere we stayed, begging for food: "Souvenir baby - san chop chop."
<p>
I liked to give away stuff like C rations if I could spare them, but would always make sure I opened them partially so they would be eaten quickly. Otherwise they might be stored and given to the enemy, or sold on the black market. It was disconcerting to me to realize the possibility that this child with the pretty smile and dark eyes could have parents who were Viet Cong.
<p>
We stayed in Tra Binh several days. Every morning I would open my eyes and there she would be. I gave her my socks to wash, and maybe a shirt, every day and would pay her a dollar or 50 cents or give her a couple cans of C rations. She hung around for a while after her chores were completed then disappeared until the next morning.
<p>
Those are the best memories I have about Vietnam--the people. I was never too busy to observe the people and what they did. The types of houses they lived in, with dirt piled up around them to ward off stray artillery rounds. The cellars the families dug inside their homes that served as their sleeping quarters. Old papa-sans carrying their food for the day in small pails, leaving at daylight and returning just before the 6PM curfew. How in the world could they do all of that work and eat so little food?
<p>
There was a determination very evident in the people. And a quiet dignity. No, I am not able to relate to you how the Vietnamese felt. But I will say that there is much about them that should be learned--by us.
<p>
